---
import LightLayout from '../../../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="Script · Claude Code" description="Structured script by blocks for Stripe Product Sense.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 pb-6">
    <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Back to hub</a>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mt-6 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">⚡</span>
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black !my-0" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Script · Claude Code</h1>
        <p class="!my-1 font-medium" style="color: var(--color-primary);">~7 min · product you know deeply, watch for feature dump</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="prose-factory">

      <div class="card !p-5 my-6" style="background: rgba(236,72,153,0.10); border: 1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.25);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">📌 How to use this script</h3>
        <p class="!mb-0">You know Claude Code in depth (you use it daily). The risk is falling into feature dump because you know too much. The anchor sentence: <strong>"assistant vs collaborator"</strong>. And under pressure, the distinction <strong>"cost per turn vs cost per task"</strong>.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[USER]</h2>
      <p>"I'm going to talk about <strong>Claude Code</strong>, which I use every day. My primary user is <strong>the senior developer with technical judgement</strong>, someone who knows what they want to build and needs to accelerate execution, not someone learning to code."</p>
      <p>"I choose this user because it's where Claude Code has real differential advantage: the senior can leverage the depth of reasoning of the model, while the junior needs guardrails and immediate feedback that IDE tools like Copilot serve better. Other segments: the junior learning, the non-developer requesting small changes, the enterprise team with strict compliance. I'll touch on them as contrast."</p>

      <h2>[SUB-SEGMENTS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>The solo builder.</strong> Works on personal projects, side projects, prototypes. Optimises for iteration speed. For them Claude Code is an exploration accelerator."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The professional integrator.</strong> Works in a large codebase, in a team. Optimises for contained changes and impact understanding. For them Claude Code is a narrow-scope assistant."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The orchestrator of long tasks.</strong> Launches multi-step tasks (massive refactor, migration, test generation). Optimises for reducing their involvement while the task is running. For them Claude Code is an autonomous agent."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"I'm going to focus on <strong>the orchestrator of long tasks</strong>, because it's where Claude Code differentiates the most from IDE-first competitors like Cursor, and where Anthropic has a structural advantage thanks to Claude's reasoning quality over long horizons."</p>

      <h2>[ECOSYSTEM]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>AI coding tools</strong>, competing with Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Cody, Aider, Continue, and increasingly with web interfaces like v0 or Lovable."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Developer infrastructure</strong>, where Claude Code sits between the IDE and the command line: CLI-first but with deep context. It competes with AI-augmented shells and with traditional automation tooling."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Anthropic API ecosystem</strong>, where Claude Code is the most visible application of the Claude API, playing a double role: revenue product and platform-adoption vehicle."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"One important layer: Claude Code's pricing model (Anthropic subscription or pay-per-token API) differs from Cursor's (fixed subscription). That creates clear competitive tension."</p>

      <h2>[ASSISTANT VS COLLABORATOR]</h2>
      <p>"Before I propose, I want to name Claude Code's central design decision: <strong>it operates as a collaborator, not as an assistant</strong>. An assistant waits for specific instructions and executes them. A collaborator understands context, anticipates steps, keeps project memory, and sometimes proposes changes to the plan. The difference shows up in how you respond to an ambiguous request: the assistant asks for more detail, the collaborator makes a first version and then iterates."</p>
      <p>"Claude Code clearly picks the second model. That decision defines the rest of the product: persistent workspace, powerful tools (Bash, edit, search), permissions to act without asking for constant confirmation."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Anchor sentence. "Assistant vs collaborator" separates you from the candidate who only describes features. It defines the product at an ontological level.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[PROPOSAL]</h2>
      <p>"For the orchestrator of long tasks, I propose <strong>negotiable progress checkpoints</strong>. When Claude Code is executing a long task (refactor, migration), it should pause at predefined points and show the user: what it has done so far, what it thinks is left, what hard decisions it has taken and why. The user can approve, redirect, or stop."</p>
      <p>"It connects to the sub-segment because it solves their number-one problem: <strong>trust over long horizons</strong>. The orchestrator can't review every action, but they also can't trust blindly. The checkpoint is the contract: 'you can act autonomously between X and Y, but you report to me when you reach Y'. And it differentiates against Cursor, which operates turn-by-turn and has no real long-task horizon."</p>

      <h2>[EDGE CASES]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, too-frequent checkpoints degrade value. If Claude Code stops every 5 minutes to report, the user loses the delegation benefit. Solution: adaptive checkpoints based on decision complexity, not fixed time."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, divergence between what Claude Code reports and what it has actually done. The report can be optimistic. Solution: the checkpoint includes a verifiable technical diff, not just a natural-language description."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, a task the model can't complete but doesn't recognise that. Solution: the checkpoint includes an explicit confidence signal ('I'm sure about this' vs 'this needs your judgement') based on test coverage, ambiguity detected, or changes outside the original scope."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[RISKS: TIGER + PAPER TIGER]</h2>
      <p>"<strong>🐅 Tiger:</strong> token cost. Long tasks with checkpoints consume context exponentially. As the task grows, the reports become more expensive to generate well. Mitigation: aggressive context caching, compress old history, and tiered pricing where long tasks cost more."</p>
      <p>"<strong>📰 Paper Tiger:</strong> 'Cursor is going to eat Claude Code on developer productivity'. Looks plausible but isn't. Cursor competes at the moment of writing code in one specific file. Claude Code competes at the moment of orchestrating changes across files and repos. Two different products at two different abstraction levels. The professional developer uses both: Cursor for the file they're in, Claude Code for the task that spans 20 files."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Anchor sentence under pressure. "Cursor in the file, Claude Code in the task". Separates you from simplistic comparisons.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[METRICS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Target:</strong> tasks completed autonomously per session without corrective intervention. Measures the real value of delegation."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Leading:</strong> checkpoint approval rate in first 14 days. Target 80%."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Lagging:</strong> weekly retention of orchestrators at 12 weeks. Target +15pp over baseline without the feature."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Guard rail:</strong> rollback rate of changes committed by Claude Code. Cannot rise more than 3% absolute. If it does, autonomy is breaking more than it fixes."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[TRANSPLANT]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'OK, now do it for non-developers who want to modify code without understanding it deeply'."</p>
      <p>"<strong>OK, let me pause. This changes a lot.</strong>"</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, I assumed the user's technical judgement. The non-developer can't evaluate whether Claude Code took the right decision at a checkpoint. The main feedback loop breaks."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, I assumed ability to read diffs. The non-developer doesn't understand the technical diff; I have to replace it with a semantic description of the change ('I've added an optional email field to the contact form')."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, I assumed the user's infrastructure: git, terminal, IDE. The non-developer is probably on a web interface, with no CLI access."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"With those assumptions broken, my proposal changes. Instead of 'negotiable checkpoints with a technical diff', I'd propose <strong>visual preview plus safe sandbox</strong>. The non-developer makes the request, Claude Code generates the change in an isolated sandbox, shows the user the behaviour before and after in natural language, and applies it only if the user confirms. It moves from 'autonomy with technical reporting' to 'demonstration with visual approval'. And the product stops being CLI, it becomes web-first."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Careful here. The transplant to non-developers turns the product into something else (closer to Lovable or v0). That's the smart observation: it's not Claude Code adapted, it's a different product.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[IF THEY PUSH BACK]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'frequent checkpoints make the product more expensive. Isn't that a contradiction if your argument is delegation?'"</p>
      <p>"Good question. Let me distinguish two things I was conflating: <strong>cost per turn and cost per task</strong>. A cheap turn isn't the same as a cheap task: if I need 50 turns to complete the task, a task with 5 expensive turns can be cheaper overall. Checkpoints add cost per turn but potentially reduce cost per task, because they prevent the scenario where Claude Code goes down the wrong path for 30 turns before the user notices. The metric that matters is cost per successfully completed task, not cost per turn."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 10 with the finer distinction specific to agentic products. "Cost per turn vs cost per task" is internal vocabulary of the teams building these products. Stripe will recognise it.</p>
      </div>

      <hr class="my-10" />

      <div class="card !p-6 my-8" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">🎯 The three anchor sentences</h3>
        <ol class="!mb-0">
          <li><strong>"Claude Code operates as a collaborator, not as an assistant."</strong></li>
          <li><strong>"Cursor competes in the file, Claude Code competes in the task."</strong></li>
          <li><strong>"The metric that matters is cost per task, not cost per turn."</strong></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-3 mt-10">
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/whatsapp" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← WhatsApp</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Hub</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/youtube" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">YouTube →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</LightLayout>
